+<body>
+  <div class="page">
+    <header class="hero" id="top">
+      <div class="eyebrow">Build Small Hackathon Brief</div>
+      <h1>Archive Detective</h1>
+      <p class="lead">
+        A playable micro-mystery machine built from real public-domain newspaper fragments,
+        where OCR and multimodal perception are the game mechanic instead of hidden infrastructure.
+      </p>
+      <div class="chip-row" aria-label="Key tags">
+        <span class="chip accent">Chosen concept</span>
+        <span class="chip">Adventure track</span>
+        <span class="chip">OpenBMB fit</span>
+        <span class="chip">Public-data viable</span>
+        <span class="chip">Modal-friendly moat</span>
+      </div>
+
+      <div class="hero-grid">
+        <div class="hero-card">
+          <h2 style="font-size:28px;">Why this wins</h2>
+          <p style="max-width: var(--reading); color:#e8eef5;">
+            Most public-data AI projects become guides, dashboards, or archive chatbots. This one becomes a <strong>game</strong>.
+            The weirdness comes from the source material itself: classifieds, half-broken OCR, old headlines, maps, and tiny human dramas.
+            The model is load-bearing because it has to read the fragment, structure it, surface clues, and turn the fragment into a solvable case.
+          </p>
+          <div class="meta-list" aria-label="Summary metrics">
+            <div class="meta-item">
+              <strong>Novelty</strong>
+              <span class="good">High</span>
+            </div>
+            <div class="meta-item">
+              <strong>Demo clarity</strong>
+              <span class="good">Immediate</span>
+            </div>
+            <div class="meta-item">
+              <strong>Sponsor fit</strong>
+              <span class="good">OpenBMB OCR-native</span>
+            </div>
+            <div class="meta-item">
+              <strong>Build risk</strong>
+              <span class="warn">Medium, but bounded</span>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+          <div class="toolbar" role="group" aria-label="Copy actions">
+            <button type="button" data-copy-target="pitch-copy">Copy pitch</button>
+            <button type="button" data-copy-target="demo-copy">Copy demo beat</button>
+            <button type="button" data-copy-target="build-copy">Copy MVP checklist</button>
+          </div>
+        </div>
+
+        <div class="hero-card" aria-labelledby="thirty-second-demo">
+          <h2 id="thirty-second-demo" style="font-size:24px;">30-second demo beat</h2>
+          <ol class="checklist">
+            <li>Show a bizarre real newspaper clipping from a public archive.</li>
+            <li>Let the model OCR it live and surface named entities, locations, mood, and clue fragments.</li>
+            <li>Watch the system generate evidence cards and a branching lead tree.</li>
+            <li>Pick a lead. Hear a voiced suspect or witness snippet.</li>
+            <li>Reveal that the fragment was real, public-domain, and stranger than fiction.</li>
+          </ol>
+          <p class="footer-note">
+            The strongest emotional note is not “look what the AI can say.” It is “look what the AI can <em>see</em>, salvage, and turn into play</em>.”
+          </p>
+        </div>
+      </div>
+    </header>
+
+    <div class="layout">
+      <aside class="sticky-toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
+        <h3>Contents</h3>
+        <nav>
+          <a href="#summary">Executive Summary</a>
+          <a href="#comparison">Concept Comparison</a>
+          <a href="#wins">Why This Idea Wins</a>
+          <a href="#mvp">MVP Experience</a>
+          <a href="#pipeline">Data Pipeline</a>
+          <a href="#models">Model and Modal Strategy</a>
+          <a href="#screens">UI and Screen Spec</a>
+          <a href="#demo">Submission Story</a>
+          <a href="#sequence">Build Sequence</a>
+        </nav>
+      </aside>
+
+      <main class="stack">
+        <section id="summary" class="panel">
+          <div class="section-kicker">Executive Summary</div>
+          <h2>Build the weirdest thing that still demos cleanly</h2>
+          <p style="max-width: var(--reading);">
+            Given the constraints that matter most here, <strong>public-only data</strong>, a desire to avoid saturated categories,
+            and a desire to win sponsor attention without chasing the NVIDIA hardware angle, <strong>Archive Detective</strong> is the strongest path.
+            It is more original than a museum guide, easier to explain than a poetic specimen experience, and more game-like than the current crop
+            of archive narrators.
+          </p>
+          <div class="cards">
+            <article class="score-card">
+              <div class="label">Track fit</div>
+              <div class="value good">Adventure</div>
+              <p>Delight, originality, and AI doing the fun thing are all core, not bolted on.</p>
+            </article>
+            <article class="score-card">
+              <div class="label">Sponsor angle</div>
+              <div class="value good">OpenBMB</div>
+              <p>OCR and multimodal grounding are visible. MiniCPM-V 4.6 has a clear job to do.</p>
+            </article>
+            <article class="score-card">
+              <div class="label">Moat</div>
+              <div class="value info">Content pipeline</div>
+              <p>Use Modal for snippet ranking, clue typing, evals, or a tiny classifier. Not a giant finetune.</p>
+            </article>
+          </div>
+          <div class="callout">
+            <strong>Core framing:</strong> do not pitch this as historical storytelling. Pitch it as a
+            <strong>playable micro-mystery machine built from real archival fragments</strong>.
+          </div>
+        </section>
+
+        <section id="comparison" class="panel">
+          <div class="section-kicker">Concept Comparison</div>
+          <h2>Why this beats the other finalists</h2>
+          <table class="comparison-table">
+            <thead>
+              <tr>
+                <th scope="col">Concept</th>
+                <th scope="col">What is great</th>
+                <th scope="col">Where it weakens</th>
+                <th scope="col">Call</th>
+              </tr>
+            </thead>
+            <tbody>
+              <tr class="winner-row">
+                <td><strong>Archive Detective</strong></td>
+                <td>Public data is rich, weird, keyless, and OCR-native. The concept is obviously a game. The demo can be understood in seconds.</td>
+                <td>Needs disciplined scope so it becomes a mystery engine, not an archive browser.</td>
+                <td class="good"><strong>Winner</strong></td>
+              </tr>
+              <tr>
+                <td><strong>Specimen Seance</strong></td>
+                <td>Beautiful images, eerie mood, and strong label-reading angle.</td>
+                <td>Can easily become a tasteful academic artifact instead of a sticky interactive toy.</td>
+                <td class="warn"><strong>Backup</strong></td>
+              </tr>
+              <tr>
+                <td><strong>Museum of Misread Futures</strong></td>
+                <td>Open APIs, huge public-domain inventory, easy to source and remix.</td>
+                <td>Too easy to drift into generic “AI museum guide” territory unless the curation game is exceptional.</td>
+                <td class="warn"><strong>Interesting, but weaker</strong></td>
+              </tr>
+            </tbody>
+          </table>
+
+          <details style="margin-top:18px;">
+            <summary>What we are explicitly not building</summary>
+            <div class="chips" style="margin-top:14px;">
+              <span class="chip">Generic archive chatbot</span>
+              <span class="chip">Map-based history narrator</span>
+              <span class="chip">Image-to-story wrapper</span>
+              <span class="chip">Public-data dashboard</span>
+              <span class="chip">Emergency response copilot</span>
+              <span class="chip">Pantry / allergy scanner</span>
+            </div>
+          </details>
+        </section>
+
+        <section id="wins" class="panel">
+          <div class="section-kicker">Why This Idea Wins</div>
+          <h2>It uses public data without feeling like a data project</h2>
+          <div class="mini-grid">
+            <article class="small-card">
+              <h4>Weirdness density</h4>
+              <p>Old newspapers are full of accidental micro-dramas: cryptic classifieds, vanished persons, coded personal ads, bad OCR, tiny maps, missing context. The archive already contains the game material.</p>
+            </article>
+            <article class="small-card">
+              <h4>AI is load-bearing</h4>
